	doi = {10.1109/PIERS62282.2024.10618591},
	abstract = {Remote sensing technology shows huge advantages in obtaining large-scale, high spatio-temporal resolution soil moisture (SM) datasets. However, the high variability across different remote sensing SM datasets induced by different retrieval algorithms and different radiative transfer models used in these algorithms presents a considerable challenge to get the right choice in different applications. To overcome this challenge, we proposed a comprehensive multi-source SM fusion framework based on machine learning models. This framework uncovers intrinsic connections between multi-source SM datasets and various geographic and climatic factors, enhancing the quality of multi-source SM datasets and mitigating data uncertainties. The framework consists of two critical processes: firstly, the identification of key environmental factors closely related to SM spatio-temporal dynamics, and secondly, the rational stratification and sampling of data samples across the whole area. A stratified k-fold cross-validation method was employed to train and validate the machine learning models. We evaluated the fusion dataset accuracy based on 594 ground-observed SM stations. Results demonstrated improved performance of the fusion framework after incorporating geographic and climatic information. The simulation performance hierarchy was observed as follows: Fusion of multi-source SM datasets and geographic-climatic environmental factors (median R2 ∈ [0.32,0.52]) {\textgreater} Fusion considering only multi-source soil moisture datasets (median R2 ∈ [0.23,0.36]) {\textgreater} Fusion considering only geographic-climatic environmental factors (median R2 ∈ [0.11,0.19]). Additionally, the fusion datasets exhibited higher accuracy than single satellite/reanalysis SM datasets. The fusion dataset I, constructed from separate watersheds (median CC: 0.69–0.82, median RMSE: 0.063–0.067m3/m3), outperformed fusion dataset II, constructed from the whole area (median CC: 0.67–0.78, median RMSE: 0.071–0.089m3/m3). The high-quality SM dataset obtained through this fusion approach seamlessly integrates information from multi-sources SM datasets, groundbased SM observations, and geographic-climatic environmental factors. This integration is poised to enhance applications in regional hydrology, ecology, agriculture, and meteorology.},
